00:00:12.877 --> 00:00:14.460
CASEY RODRIGUEZ: So
we ended last time

00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:18.127
with these elementary
properties that you

00:00:18.127 --> 00:00:19.605
know about the absolute value.

00:00:22.420 --> 00:00:29.400
So let me prove one more theorem
about the absolute value, which

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.680
maybe you didn't
cover in calculus.

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:42.070
But it's of
fundamental importance

00:00:42.070 --> 00:00:47.770
in real analysis, which is
the triangle inequality, which

00:00:47.770 --> 00:00:55.630
states that for all xy in R,
the absolute value of x plus y

00:00:55.630 --> 00:01:01.000
is less than or equal to
the absolute value of x

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:02.590
plus the absolute value of y.

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:07.650
So why is it called the
triangle inequality?

00:01:07.650 --> 00:01:14.410
Well, let me-- instead of
x and y being real numbers,

00:01:14.410 --> 00:01:18.650
let's think of these as vectors.

00:01:18.650 --> 00:01:22.670
So there's x.

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:30.310
Let's say y.

00:01:30.310 --> 00:01:38.275
And then vector x
plus y is this side.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.380
Then what this is stating
is that the length

00:01:47.380 --> 00:01:50.500
of one of these sides
of this triangle

00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:52.780
is less than or equal
to the sum of the two

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:55.863
sides, the sum of the lengths
of the other two sides

00:01:55.863 --> 00:01:56.530
of the triangle.

00:02:00.980 --> 00:02:06.120
So that's why it's called
the triangle inequality.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:14.070
OK, so the proof is
not very difficult,

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:19.690
although this
inequality is probably

00:02:19.690 --> 00:02:21.880
one of the three most
useful things you'll

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:25.400
learn in this class if you go
on to study more analysis--

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:26.740
the other one being--

00:02:26.740 --> 00:02:29.380
OK, so I'm coming--

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:32.020
this is knowledge from PDE.

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:35.560
So I guess I'm viewing it
through that lens of what

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:36.910
I find useful in PDEs.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:40.300
But triangle inequality,
integration by parts,

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:47.780
change of variables, those
three power the analysis machine

00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:49.860
that I'm most familiar with.

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:52.280
So how to prove the
triangle inequality--

00:02:56.780 --> 00:03:05.000
if x and y is an R, then
clearly, by property number 6,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.400
the x is less than or
equal to the absolute value

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.610
of x and y is less than or equal
to the absolute value of y.

00:03:10.610 --> 00:03:13.040
So their sum is less than or
equal to the absolute value

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:14.030
of x plus y.

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:22.240
And not only that, I can
replace x by minus x and I

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:27.090
get minus x plus
minus y, this is

00:03:27.090 --> 00:03:31.860
less than or equal to the
absolute value of minus x

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:33.690
plus the absolute
value of minus y.

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:37.185
But this is just absolute
value of x plus y.

00:03:44.040 --> 00:03:48.430
And both of these
therefore imply--

00:03:48.430 --> 00:04:05.660
so if I just take this and
multiply through by minus 1,

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:09.320
this inequality,
which, by number 5

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:13.340
in the properties that we
proved, for the absolute value

00:04:13.340 --> 00:04:16.010
implies that the absolute
value of x plus y is less than

00:04:16.010 --> 00:04:21.290
or equal to the
absolute value of x

00:04:21.290 --> 00:04:25.690
plus the absolute value of y.

00:04:25.690 --> 00:04:31.750
So let me just make a remark
about the reverse triangle

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:41.630
Inequality, which will make an
appearance in your assignment.

00:04:41.630 --> 00:04:47.750
And so this involves the
absolute value of x minus y

00:04:47.750 --> 00:04:50.840
and the absolute value
of the difference

00:04:50.840 --> 00:04:52.700
in the absolute values.

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:53.570
Why is it reverse?

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:54.965
Because the inequality reverses.

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:06.810
The absolute value of x minus
the absolute value and y,

00:05:06.810 --> 00:05:08.470
take the absolute value.

00:05:08.470 --> 00:05:11.280
This is less than or equal
to the absolute value

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:12.090
of x minus y.

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:14.940
And you'll prove this
in the assignment.

00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:18.750
So these two-- so this follows
from the triangle inequality.

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:21.522
But these two inequalities
get used quite a bit.

00:05:21.522 --> 00:05:23.730
And we'll use them quite a
bit throughout the course.

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:41.710
All right, so let me take
a minute to reconnect R

00:05:41.710 --> 00:05:46.660
with what you know and love
from calculus, namely decimals.

00:05:46.660 --> 00:05:50.960
And we're going to
use this fact about R

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:54.980
to answer a natural
question that maybe you're

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:58.800
asking yourself, which
is the following.

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:00.500
So let me raise
this as a question.

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:08.270
So this first part
is not the question.

00:06:08.270 --> 00:06:12.370
We've already addressed this in
the first assignment, the fact

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:14.560
that the rationals is countable.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.540
In fact, you did it for
the positive rationals.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:18.940
But if the positive
rationals are countable,

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:24.520
you can then prove that all
rationals are countable.

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:33.663
And a natural question--
is R countable?

00:06:33.663 --> 00:06:35.330
Or is the set of real
numbers countable?

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:44.850
So in the end--

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:47.430
I'm not going to leave
you in suspense--

00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:50.100
the answer is no.

00:06:50.100 --> 00:06:51.532
And we're going to prove this.

00:06:51.532 --> 00:06:53.865
But let me just make a few
remarks about what this says.

00:06:56.550 --> 00:07:02.040
So it's the following.

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:08.200
So if Q-- so this is
not a proof of this.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:12.260
I'm just going to make a
remark based on this answer.

00:07:12.260 --> 00:07:32.120
So since R is uncountable
and Q is countable,

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:41.810
this implies that R takeaway Q,
the set of irrational numbers,

00:07:41.810 --> 00:07:47.890
is, in fact, uncountable.

00:07:47.890 --> 00:07:48.390
Why?

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:55.070
So I'm just going to say
in words why this is true.

00:07:55.070 --> 00:07:58.780
So suppose otherwise that
both the rational numbers

00:07:58.780 --> 00:08:01.210
and the irrationals
are countable.

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:03.700
Then you can map in
a bijective fashion

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:10.130
the rationals to the natural
numbers and the irrationals

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:11.510
also to the natural numbers.

00:08:11.510 --> 00:08:15.050
But then you can map those
natural numbers to 0, minus 1,

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:18.120
minus 2, minus 3, and so on.

00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:20.390
So then you find that
there is a bijection

00:08:20.390 --> 00:08:24.320
from Q to the natural
numbers and the irrationals

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:27.200
to the integers less
than or equal to 0.

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:31.040
And therefore, there's bijection
from R to the integers.

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:34.720
But the integers are countable,
which would contradict the fact

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:36.760
that R is uncountable.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:40.630
Therefore, the set of
irrationals is uncountable.

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:45.370
So in short, if you
didn't follow that,

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:48.850
the set of irrationals
is uncountable

00:08:48.850 --> 00:08:53.650
because otherwise this would
force R to be countable.

00:08:53.650 --> 00:08:56.328
Now, I haven't proved yet
that R is uncountable.

00:08:56.328 --> 00:08:57.620
We'll do that in just a minute.

00:08:57.620 --> 00:09:02.290
And we'll use a theorem about
decimal expansions for--

00:09:02.290 --> 00:09:04.105
or decimal representations
of real numbers.

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:15.440
So now, connecting
rationals and irrationals

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:19.580
to what you've seen
since you were small,

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:21.260
so to decimals, we simply--

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:31.140
we typically-- we think
of rational numbers

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:44.080
as in terms of decimal
representations.

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:46.640
What does that mean?

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:49.030
That means we take--

00:09:49.030 --> 00:10:01.420
if x is in Q, then we'll write x
as some number times some digit

00:10:01.420 --> 00:10:10.330
times 10 to the k plus 10
to the k minus 1 plus d0.

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:15.700
And then we go to the
tenths spot, so d to the--

00:10:15.700 --> 00:10:19.570
d minus 1 10 to
the minus 1 plus--

00:10:19.570 --> 00:10:20.710
so this is discussion.

00:10:20.710 --> 00:10:26.640
I'm not stating any
theorems right now,

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:35.920
until we get down to maybe
some last decimal spot.

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:57.540
And with these digits,
a subset of 0, 1, 9.

00:10:57.540 --> 00:11:00.190
So all I'm saying is typically
we think of x as this way.

00:11:00.190 --> 00:11:14.520
And then we write x as dk, dk
minus 1, d minus 1, d minus 2,

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:15.150
and so on.

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:24.380
I'm using this notation
because I'm going to be--

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:26.380
this is the notation I
need to state the theorem

00:11:26.380 --> 00:11:27.970
about the real numbers.

00:11:27.970 --> 00:11:33.010
But it's quite silly that
I'm about to write this down

00:11:33.010 --> 00:11:36.130
in this setting.

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:38.470
Welcome to MIT.

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:48.610
So for example, 1
times 10 plus 1 times

00:11:48.610 --> 00:11:53.185
10 to the 0 plus 1
times 10 to the minus 1.

00:11:56.230 --> 00:12:04.950
This is supposed to represent
the number 11.1, which

00:12:04.950 --> 00:12:06.180
is the rational number.

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:25.640
It's quite funny that I had to
think about that for a minute

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:28.400
to go from the decimal expansion
to the rational numbers.

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:33.170
But don't give me
too hard of a time.

00:12:33.170 --> 00:12:37.695
In a lot of at least
pure math, we typically

00:12:37.695 --> 00:12:39.070
write things in
rational numbers.

00:12:39.070 --> 00:12:40.720
We don't write in decimal--

00:12:40.720 --> 00:12:43.480
I haven't had to write in
decimal expansion in quite

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:44.360
some time.

00:12:44.360 --> 00:12:48.670
Anyways, now, of course,
not all rational numbers

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:51.280
can be written as a
finite decimal expansion.

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:53.680
For example, 1/3
you have to write

00:12:53.680 --> 00:13:01.940
as 0.33333 and so on and so on.

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:05.110
So that's not necessarily
covered under the discussion

00:13:05.110 --> 00:13:07.790
that I have right here.

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:10.540
But it will be
covered in what I'm

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:13.760
about to say for
the real numbers.

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:16.180
So we could cover 1/3.

00:13:16.180 --> 00:13:18.340
And then we can also
cover every real number

00:13:18.340 --> 00:13:22.630
if we allow infinite
decimal representations.

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:24.910
So I'll use the word decimal
expansions or decimal

00:13:24.910 --> 00:13:27.430
representations
interchangeably there.

00:13:27.430 --> 00:13:31.538
So let me make a definition.

00:13:31.538 --> 00:13:33.580
And what I'm going to
state is about real numbers

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:35.380
between 0 and 1.

00:13:35.380 --> 00:13:37.660
Of course, if you want to
talk about real numbers

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:41.500
bigger than 1, then you
just tack on 1 to the--

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:43.285
if you like, to the d0 place.

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:54.340
So the infinite part is
having to deal with what

00:13:54.340 --> 00:13:57.560
comes after the decimal point.

00:13:57.560 --> 00:14:00.290
So the let me make
the following.

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:03.220
So this is a
rigorous definition.

00:14:03.220 --> 00:14:06.550
Let x in 0, 1 excluding 0.

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:16.201
And let d minus j
be in 0, 1 to 9.

00:14:24.767 --> 00:14:29.130
for j, a natural number.

00:14:29.130 --> 00:14:34.290
So we say x is--

00:14:38.590 --> 00:14:40.480
so what does it
mean to say that x

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:43.990
is given by an infinite
decimal expansion

00:14:43.990 --> 00:14:48.130
or given by an infinite
decimal representation?

00:14:48.130 --> 00:14:52.690
We say x is represented
by the digits.

00:15:04.070 --> 00:15:13.800
And we write x is equal to d
minus 1, d minus 2, d minus 3.

00:15:17.740 --> 00:15:21.110
If-- so this is the
precise meaning of this.

00:15:21.110 --> 00:15:27.955
If x is equal to the
supremum of the set--

00:15:31.020 --> 00:15:35.010
so I take a finite
decimal expansion.

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:46.760
And then so I get a number
for each n, a natural number.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:51.200
So the first one is just d
minus 1 10 to the minus 1.

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:54.260
And then for n equals 2, I
tack on next hundredths place,

00:15:54.260 --> 00:15:55.920
and then the thousandths place.

00:15:55.920 --> 00:16:00.650
And so I get a set
of real numbers.

00:16:00.650 --> 00:16:02.720
If I take its
supremum and I get x,

00:16:02.720 --> 00:16:08.810
then I say that x is represented
by these digits or that x--

00:16:08.810 --> 00:16:12.200
or that this gives a
decimal representation of x.

00:16:12.200 --> 00:16:25.075
So that you see this lines
up with what you know,

00:16:25.075 --> 00:16:32.470
if I look at 0.250000, remember
this is now the sup of what?

00:16:35.350 --> 00:16:36.640
Of a certain set.

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:39.400
So let me do first this guy.

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:43.330
So this is 2/10.

00:16:43.330 --> 00:16:48.070
And then now, I add the
hundredths place plus 5/100,

00:16:48.070 --> 00:16:53.980
and then 2/10 plus 5/100--
this is a set, remember--

00:16:53.980 --> 00:16:59.590
plus 0/1000 over plus--

00:16:59.590 --> 00:17:03.280
and at each next
guy, I'm supposed

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:06.069
to take this and
add on another 0.

00:17:06.069 --> 00:17:13.210
So as a set, this is just a
set containing two elements,

00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:24.930
namely 2/10 and 25/100.

00:17:24.930 --> 00:17:28.420
And so this is
bigger than that guy.

00:17:28.420 --> 00:17:31.770
So the supremum is
25/100, which equals 1/4.

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:33.790
OK, so all of that
to tell you that,

00:17:33.790 --> 00:17:36.400
yes, this definition should--

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:39.510
or at least does
ring true with what

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:51.040
you were taught, that 1/4
is equal to 0.25, all right?

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:56.715
OK, so now that what we're done
with the triangle inequality,

00:17:56.715 --> 00:17:57.715
I'm going to erase this.

00:18:34.220 --> 00:18:37.360
And so this is the
last bit of discussion

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:40.693
about the elementary
properties of the real numbers.

00:18:40.693 --> 00:18:42.985
Next, we'll be talking about
sequences of real numbers.

00:18:46.900 --> 00:18:54.310
OK, so all right, so I
have this definition.

00:18:54.310 --> 00:18:57.550
The fundamental theorem
about the real numbers

00:18:57.550 --> 00:19:00.460
is that every real number, at
least in this setting between 0

00:19:00.460 --> 00:19:05.690
and 1, can be represented
by a set of digits

00:19:05.690 --> 00:19:11.070
or it has a decimal
representation.

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:14.310
And every decimal-- if you
like, every set of digits

00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:17.340
corresponds to a
decimal representation

00:19:17.340 --> 00:19:18.550
of a real number.

00:19:18.550 --> 00:19:24.340
So let me state the
second thing I said first.

00:19:24.340 --> 00:19:56.870
So for every set of digits d
minus j with each of these d

00:19:56.870 --> 00:20:10.530
minus j's in 0 up
to 9, then there

00:20:10.530 --> 00:20:23.660
exists a unique x in
closed interval 0, 1 such

00:20:23.660 --> 00:20:28.700
that x is equal to d minus 1--

00:20:28.700 --> 00:20:30.680
with this decimal
representation.

00:20:33.320 --> 00:20:38.150
So you give me some
digits and I can

00:20:38.150 --> 00:20:40.610
find a unique real
number that has

00:20:40.610 --> 00:20:44.000
that decimal representation.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:48.020
Now, before I state the
second part of the theorem,

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:49.970
this says that I
give you digits,

00:20:49.970 --> 00:20:51.600
I get a unique real number.

00:20:51.600 --> 00:20:53.900
Now, you ask about
the other direction.

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:57.620
If I have a real number, do
I get a unique set of digits?

00:20:57.620 --> 00:21:01.430
And of course, that is
not true necessarily

00:21:01.430 --> 00:21:16.960
because, for example, 1/2, this
is equal to 0.500 and so on.

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:22.420
But this is also equal
to 0.4999 and so on.

00:21:22.420 --> 00:21:31.370
So yes, every set of digits
gives me a unique real number.

00:21:31.370 --> 00:21:32.990
So if I gave you
these digits, they

00:21:32.990 --> 00:21:34.940
would spit out 1/2 and only 1/2.

00:21:34.940 --> 00:21:37.940
It wouldn't spit out 1/4.

00:21:37.940 --> 00:21:40.260
But if you give
me a real number,

00:21:40.260 --> 00:21:46.480
there does not necessarily
exist a unique set

00:21:46.480 --> 00:21:49.570
of digits giving a decimal
expansion for that number.

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:52.060
So I can have two different
decimal expansions.

00:21:52.060 --> 00:21:54.745
I have 0.5 and I have 0.4999.

00:21:54.745 --> 00:21:56.620
I will always have at
least one, but it's not

00:21:56.620 --> 00:21:58.300
necessarily unique.

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:02.590
But we can single
out one unique choice

00:22:02.590 --> 00:22:06.730
by requiring that, in some
sense, if I were to truncate

00:22:06.730 --> 00:22:10.660
it, then the decimal expansion
would be less than the number

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:13.870
I'm looking at and
wanting to expand.

00:22:13.870 --> 00:22:17.190
So that's the second
part of this theorem,

00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:28.430
is that for every x in
0, 1, now excluding 0,

00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:36.070
there exists unique digits--

00:22:44.140 --> 00:22:47.530
and as before, these
are in 0 up to 9--

00:22:47.530 --> 00:22:53.560
such that x is--

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:56.230
such that these give a
decimal representation of x.

00:22:58.760 --> 00:23:04.610
And so what singles out a
choice if we're ever coming up

00:23:04.610 --> 00:23:05.720
against these two things?

00:23:08.510 --> 00:23:17.128
And if I truncate the
