00:46:30.095 --> 00:46:31.720
And when we refer to
them, we'll either

00:46:31.720 --> 00:46:34.360
write them like that
or with curly brackets

00:46:34.360 --> 00:46:37.568
around an expression
for x sub n.

00:46:44.270 --> 00:46:48.755
So for example, if I
were to write this,

00:46:48.755 --> 00:47:00.260
this means this is the sequence
given by 1, 1/2, 1/3, 1/4, 1/5,

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:00.920
and so on.

00:47:05.530 --> 00:47:06.030
OK.

00:47:54.400 --> 00:48:00.650
So here's another definition.

00:48:00.650 --> 00:48:04.570
So a sequence is bounded
if, in some sense,

00:48:04.570 --> 00:48:08.180
it doesn't run off to
arbitrarily large values.

00:48:08.180 --> 00:48:28.330
So sequence x sub n is
bounded if there exists

00:48:28.330 --> 00:48:30.760
some real number b
bigger than or equal

00:48:30.760 --> 00:48:39.310
to 0 such that for all n
in the natural numbers xn

00:48:39.310 --> 00:48:43.900
is less than or equal
to b in absolute value.

00:48:43.900 --> 00:48:50.140
So again, for example, if
we take a look back at both

00:48:50.140 --> 00:48:52.780
of those two sequences--

00:48:52.780 --> 00:48:58.400
1, 1, 1, and the
sequence 1 over n--

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:02.970
these are bounded.

00:49:02.970 --> 00:49:03.470
Why?

00:49:03.470 --> 00:49:04.910
Because every element in this--

00:49:08.420 --> 00:49:14.000
I shouldn't say element, but
every entry in this sequence

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:15.140
is equal to 1.

00:49:15.140 --> 00:49:16.910
So it's bounded by 1.

00:49:16.910 --> 00:49:21.980
And every entry in this sequence
is less than or equal to 1.

00:49:21.980 --> 00:49:23.900
So it's bounded by
1 in absolute value.

00:49:23.900 --> 00:49:24.990
It's also positive.

00:49:24.990 --> 00:49:27.280
So they're both bounded.

00:49:27.280 --> 00:49:35.680
Another example is the
sequence minus 1 to the n.

00:49:35.680 --> 00:49:41.530
So I'll write equals,
although this shouldn't-- this

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:42.530
doesn't mean anything.

00:49:42.530 --> 00:49:45.490
I'm just going to write it--

00:49:45.490 --> 00:49:49.260
write it-- or start listing
the entries-- minus 1,

00:49:49.260 --> 00:49:54.280
1, minus 1, 1, minus 1, 1.

00:49:54.280 --> 00:50:01.990
This is also bounded because
the absolute value of minus 1

00:50:01.990 --> 00:50:02.830
to the n is 1.

00:50:02.830 --> 00:50:06.470
So that's bounded
by 1 for all n.

00:50:06.470 --> 00:50:07.820
So what's a non-example?

00:50:16.430 --> 00:50:20.800
The sequence n-- in
other words, this

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:26.960
is the sequence 1, 2,
3, 4, 5, and so on.

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:34.240
Now, precisely why is it un--
so I should say this is bounded.

00:50:38.530 --> 00:50:48.390
And otherwise, I'll refer to x
sub n as unbounded, unbounded.

00:50:52.470 --> 00:50:53.520
So why is it unbounded?

00:50:53.520 --> 00:50:56.670
Because the entries are getting
larger and larger in size.

00:50:59.350 --> 00:51:02.650
But if I were to ask
you to prove this,

00:51:02.650 --> 00:51:05.020
you would have to show--

00:51:05.020 --> 00:51:07.510
and this is also a
good first exercise--

00:51:07.510 --> 00:51:10.390
what does it mean
to be unbounded.

00:51:10.390 --> 00:51:13.870
So I said this at one
point, that if you

00:51:13.870 --> 00:51:17.290
come across a reasonably
interesting definition,

00:51:17.290 --> 00:51:21.370
you should look up or try
to come up with examples.

00:51:21.370 --> 00:51:23.740
And typically, when you
do come up with examples,

00:51:23.740 --> 00:51:25.600
you should come up
with non-examples.

00:51:25.600 --> 00:51:30.320
And what that requires you to
do is negate the definition.

00:51:30.320 --> 00:51:34.420
What does it mean for
something to not be that?

00:51:34.420 --> 00:51:39.280
So even though I'm saying
that if it's not bounded

00:51:39.280 --> 00:51:41.050
I call it unbounded,
I haven't actually

00:51:41.050 --> 00:51:43.750
written a mathematical
statement to this effect

00:51:43.750 --> 00:51:45.470
on what this means.

00:51:45.470 --> 00:51:50.240
So let me make this
right here as a remark.

00:51:50.240 --> 00:51:58.560
So a sequence is
unbounded, so if it doesn't

00:51:58.560 --> 00:52:00.070
satisfy that definition.

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:02.460
So we need to negate
this definition.

00:52:02.460 --> 00:52:05.910
The definition says
this is bounded

00:52:05.910 --> 00:52:09.450
if there exists a b bigger
than or equal to 0 such

00:52:09.450 --> 00:52:12.480
that this holds for all n.

00:52:12.480 --> 00:52:16.020
Now, when I negate a there
exists, that becomes a for all.

00:52:16.020 --> 00:52:19.960
And when I negate a for all,
that becomes a there exists.

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:23.410
And then I negate
this condition.

00:52:23.410 --> 00:52:30.420
So the sequence is unbounded
if for all b bigger than

00:52:30.420 --> 00:52:37.080
or equal to 0 there exists
a natural number in n

00:52:37.080 --> 00:52:42.840
such that xn in absolute
value is bigger than b.

00:52:50.100 --> 00:52:52.800
Now, using this-- so
this is-- if you like,

00:52:52.800 --> 00:52:54.630
you can take that as
a second definition.

00:52:54.630 --> 00:52:57.870
Or it's not really a definition,
since it's just the negation

00:52:57.870 --> 00:52:59.160
of the first definition.

00:53:02.490 --> 00:53:04.710
Why is this set unbounded?

00:53:04.710 --> 00:53:07.200
Because of the
Archimedean property.

00:53:12.940 --> 00:53:15.820
So now, I'm giving you a
little short proof on why

00:53:15.820 --> 00:53:18.760
this sequence is unbounded.

00:53:18.760 --> 00:53:23.830
Let b be bigger
than or equal to 0.

00:53:23.830 --> 00:53:27.730
By the Archimedean
property, there

00:53:27.730 --> 00:53:34.030
exists a natural number
n such that n is bigger

00:53:34.030 --> 00:53:37.600
than b, which is
exactly what we wanted

00:53:37.600 --> 00:53:47.270
to prove because, in this case,
x sub n is n, is unbounded.

00:54:01.380 --> 00:54:09.640
OK, now, what does
it mean for us

00:54:09.640 --> 00:54:11.140
to have a limit of a sequence?

00:54:11.140 --> 00:54:14.272
What does a limit
of a sequence mean?

00:54:14.272 --> 00:54:15.730
What does it mean
for a real number

00:54:15.730 --> 00:54:17.950
to be the limit of a sequence?

00:54:21.293 --> 00:54:23.710
What does it mean for a sequence
to converge to something?

00:54:23.710 --> 00:54:41.000
So the sequence x sub n
converges to a real number

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:46.670
x in R if the following
condition is satisfied--

00:54:46.670 --> 00:54:55.760
if for every epsilon positive,
there exists a natural number

00:54:55.760 --> 00:55:01.940
capital M such that
for all n bigger

00:55:01.940 --> 00:55:08.270
than or equal to capital M
xn minus x absolute value

00:55:08.270 --> 00:55:10.112
is less than epsilon.

00:55:10.112 --> 00:55:11.570
Now, remember the
absolute value is

00:55:11.570 --> 00:55:13.153
meant to be something
like a distance.

00:55:13.153 --> 00:55:14.900
So what does this statement say?

00:55:14.900 --> 00:55:18.590
This says if I give you a little
bit of tolerance, epsilon,

00:55:18.590 --> 00:55:21.890
and you go far enough
out in the sequence,

00:55:21.890 --> 00:55:29.600
then the distance between that
entry in the sequence and x

00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:31.490
are very close to each other.

00:55:36.130 --> 00:55:40.030
Let me finish stating the
rest of this definition

00:55:40.030 --> 00:55:42.610
and we'll do a little
more discussion.

00:55:49.240 --> 00:55:57.660
If a sequence converges,
we say it's convergent.

00:56:05.360 --> 00:56:10.280
Otherwise, we say
it's divergent.

00:56:16.540 --> 00:56:19.750
So all right, let me draw--

00:56:19.750 --> 00:56:24.610
let me draw a little picture
of what this is meant to be.

00:56:24.610 --> 00:56:31.570
So the real numbers,
it was this--

00:56:31.570 --> 00:56:35.510
I mean, it is this
unique ordered field

00:56:35.510 --> 00:56:37.160
with the least upper
bound property.

00:56:37.160 --> 00:56:40.130
But when you think
about the real numbers,

00:56:40.130 --> 00:56:42.410
think of it as you've
always thought about it,

00:56:42.410 --> 00:56:44.790
as just the real number line.

00:56:44.790 --> 00:56:48.870
So what does this
definition mean?

00:56:48.870 --> 00:56:56.600
It means that a sequence
converges to some

00:56:56.600 --> 00:57:02.710
x if for every epsilon
I can do the following.

00:57:02.710 --> 00:57:03.530
If I look at--

00:57:12.130 --> 00:57:22.250
if I give you an epsilon and you
go on either side of x epsilon

00:57:22.250 --> 00:57:27.500
amount, then you should be
able to find a capital M so

00:57:27.500 --> 00:57:34.100
that if you look at entries
in your sequence x sub n for n

00:57:34.100 --> 00:57:37.980
bigger than or equal to
M they're in this guy.

00:57:37.980 --> 00:57:43.640
So then I should have x sub
M there, x sub M plus 1,

00:57:43.640 --> 00:57:45.560
x sub M plus 2.

00:57:45.560 --> 00:57:48.560
And in general, x sub
n should be in there,

00:57:48.560 --> 00:57:50.930
as long as n is bigger
than or equal to M.

00:57:50.930 --> 00:57:57.300
So I should be able to do
this for every epsilon.

00:57:57.300 --> 00:57:59.900
So for any amount of
tolerance epsilon,

00:57:59.900 --> 00:58:03.560
you should be able to go far
enough out in the sequence

00:58:03.560 --> 00:58:08.330
that all entries
in that sequence

00:58:08.330 --> 00:58:12.280
are within this tolerance of x.

00:58:44.740 --> 00:58:48.550
I mean, although this is a
picture of what the definition

00:58:48.550 --> 00:58:50.740
means, how should you--

00:58:50.740 --> 00:58:58.640
I mean, you've probably
gotten plenty of experience

00:58:58.640 --> 00:59:01.430
with sequences when you
were doing calculus.

00:59:01.430 --> 00:59:04.490
But what does this mean loosely?

00:59:04.490 --> 00:59:09.290
It means if I look close to x,
some little interval containing

00:59:09.290 --> 00:59:13.730
x, then all of the sequence, all
of the elements of the sequence

00:59:13.730 --> 00:59:15.755
should be eventually in this--

00:59:18.840 --> 00:59:19.840
in this little interval.

00:59:22.510 --> 00:59:24.430
Or another way to
think about it is

00:59:24.430 --> 00:59:33.280
that as I go on in the sequence,
the entries are getting closer

00:59:33.280 --> 00:59:40.960
and closer and closer to
x Now, the way one makes

00:59:40.960 --> 00:59:46.420
these last two intuitive
statements precise

00:59:46.420 --> 00:59:48.850
is via this definition.

00:59:48.850 --> 00:59:52.780
The closer and closer
part is encapsulated

00:59:52.780 --> 00:59:56.050
in this for all epsilon part.

00:59:56.050 --> 01:00:00.700
And eventually getting closer
and closer means for all n

01:00:00.700 --> 01:00:02.260
bigger than or
equal to capital M.

01:00:02.260 --> 01:00:04.870
As long as I go far enough
out in the sequence,

01:00:04.870 --> 01:00:07.420
they're getting close to x.

01:00:07.420 --> 01:00:09.445
So I hope that's pretty clear.

01:00:44.080 --> 01:00:46.750
All right, so again,
we have a definition.

01:00:50.440 --> 01:00:52.790
And it's reasonably interesting.

01:00:52.790 --> 01:00:56.840
So we should do examples,
and then also negate it.

01:00:56.840 --> 01:01:00.280
But before I do
either of those, I

01:01:00.280 --> 01:01:03.310
do want to just prove
a very simple fact

01:01:03.310 --> 01:01:07.870
about convergent
sequences, namely

01:01:07.870 --> 01:01:12.670
that if I have a sequence
which converges to x, then x

01:01:12.670 --> 01:01:15.640
is the only thing that
sequence can converge to.

01:01:15.640 --> 01:01:19.750
I cannot have a convergent
sequence which converges to two

01:01:19.750 --> 01:01:20.470
different things.

01:01:20.470 --> 01:01:22.780
Like I said, if you
go by this intuition

01:01:22.780 --> 01:01:26.080
that eventually the
x sub n's are getting

01:01:26.080 --> 01:01:28.900
closer and closer and
closer to x, well,

01:01:28.900 --> 01:01:31.090
then there's no way they
can be also getting closer

01:01:31.090 --> 01:01:34.733
to something other than x.

01:01:34.733 --> 01:01:36.400
So I just want to
prove that real quick.

01:01:36.400 --> 01:01:40.150
And then we'll do examples and
a negation of this definition.

01:01:43.531 --> 01:01:46.200
So the following theorem--

01:01:46.200 --> 01:01:52.170
and so I'm going to state
first the theorem that

01:01:52.170 --> 01:01:54.030
has nothing to do
with sequences,

01:01:54.030 --> 01:01:59.640
but is a nice way if you want
to show two things are equal.

01:01:59.640 --> 01:02:01.587
You can show they're
smaller than anything.

01:02:01.587 --> 01:02:03.420
So the first theorem
that I'm going to state

01:02:03.420 --> 01:02:15.120
is if x and y are in R and
all epsilon positive x minus y

01:02:15.120 --> 01:02:21.420
is less than epsilon,
then x equals y.

01:02:21.420 --> 01:02:23.010
This is not a
surprising statement.

01:02:23.010 --> 01:02:27.300
If I have x and y and
the distance between them

01:02:27.300 --> 01:02:29.970
is arbitrarily small, then
they have to be the same thing.

01:02:33.540 --> 01:02:34.710
So what's the proof?

01:02:37.590 --> 01:02:47.700
Suppose xy is in R. And for
all epsilon positive, x minus y

01:02:47.700 --> 01:02:48.700
is less than epsilon.

01:02:48.700 --> 01:02:50.250
So now, I want to
prove x equals y.

01:02:50.250 --> 01:02:56.460
So let's assume that this
does not hold and arrive

01:02:56.460 --> 01:02:57.370
at a contradiction.

01:02:57.370 --> 01:02:59.920
So this is a short
proof by contradiction.

01:02:59.920 --> 01:03:03.300
Suppose x does not equal y.

01:03:03.300 --> 01:03:13.360
Then remember we proved that
the absolute value of something

01:03:13.360 --> 01:03:17.800
is 0 if and only if
that thing is equal to 0

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:19.510
and it's always non-negative.

01:03:19.510 --> 01:03:22.930
So x not equal to y means the
absolute value of x minus y

01:03:22.930 --> 01:03:24.670
is less than-- is bigger than 0.

01:03:27.340 --> 01:03:32.320
Then by this
assumption, for epsilon

01:03:32.320 --> 01:03:36.040
equal to x minus
y over 2, I get--

01:03:41.260 --> 01:03:45.730
which implies if I just
subtract that over, x minus y

01:03:45.730 --> 01:03:46.720
is less than 0.

01:03:46.720 --> 01:03:52.150
So 1/2 is less than 0 or--

01:03:52.150 --> 01:03:53.980
and that's a very
false statement.

01:03:53.980 --> 01:03:56.230
We've already proven that
the absolute value is always

01:03:56.230 --> 01:03:57.970
non-negative.

01:03:57.970 --> 01:04:03.580
So if I have two real
numbers that are arbitrarily

01:04:03.580 --> 01:04:07.030
close to each other, then
they have to be the same.

01:04:07.030 --> 01:04:11.330
I'm going to use this
theorem to prove that--

01:04:11.330 --> 01:04:14.530
I don't know why
I put a 1 there--

01:04:14.530 --> 01:04:22.170
why limits-- and I have not
said that's what we call x--

01:04:22.170 --> 01:04:26.490
but why a convergent sequence
can only converge to one thing.

01:04:29.840 --> 01:04:33.580
So here is the statement
of the second theorem.

01:04:33.580 --> 01:04:40.960
If x sub n is a sequence
and it converges

01:04:40.960 --> 01:04:49.270
to x and it also converges
to y, then x equals y.

01:04:49.270 --> 01:04:55.625
So a convergent sequence can
only converge to one thing.

01:04:55.625 --> 01:04:57.500
And again, like I said,
there should be clear

01:04:57.500 --> 01:05:03.680
because what's happening is if
I have two things that are not

01:05:03.680 --> 01:05:05.990
equal and x sub
n converges to x,

01:05:05.990 --> 01:05:10.100
that means as long as I go far
enough out in the sequence,

01:05:10.100 --> 01:05:16.340
they're supposed to be here in
this small interval around x.

01:05:16.340 --> 01:05:20.750
Well, if they're supposed
to be converging to y,

01:05:20.750 --> 01:05:22.340
if I go far enough
out, they're also

01:05:22.340 --> 01:05:28.270
supposed to be over here as
long as I go far enough out.

01:05:28.270 --> 01:05:33.200
But you can't be in two
places at once ever.

01:05:33.200 --> 01:05:35.800
And so that's why
x must equal y.

01:05:43.130 --> 01:05:44.780
Although, I suppose
that now we're

01:05:44.780 --> 01:05:48.530
doing all the classes
online, some are recorded.

01:05:48.530 --> 01:05:54.040
So you can be two places at
once, but at least not here.

01:05:54.040 --> 01:05:56.950
OK, so we're going
to use this theorem

01:05:56.950 --> 01:05:58.360
to prove this statement.

01:06:02.910 --> 01:06:15.110
Suppose-- converges to x and y.

01:06:15.110 --> 01:06:17.840
And I want to verify that
for all epsilon positive

01:06:17.840 --> 01:06:19.857
the absolute value of
x minus y is less than

01:06:19.857 --> 01:06:20.690
or equal to epsilon.

01:06:27.340 --> 01:06:30.310
Now, remember if I'm proving
something for all epsilon,

01:06:30.310 --> 01:06:35.860
I have to-- that means I do
it for arbitrary epsilon.

01:06:35.860 --> 01:06:39.760
You get points just for setting
let epsilon be positive.

01:06:39.760 --> 01:06:42.640
OK, now, I want to show the
absolute value of x minus y

01:06:42.640 --> 01:06:44.440
is less than or
equal to epsilon.

01:06:44.440 --> 01:06:46.900
And we're basically going to
do the argument that I just

01:06:46.900 --> 01:06:47.400
erased.

01:06:49.870 --> 01:07:03.400
So since x sub n
converges to x, that

01:07:03.400 --> 01:07:10.860
implies that there exists a
natural number M1 such that

01:07:10.860 --> 01:07:14.400
for all n bigger
than or equal to M1,

01:07:14.400 --> 01:07:19.140
x sub n minus x is less
than epsilon over 2.

01:07:19.140 --> 01:07:20.502
Why the epsilon over 2?

01:07:20.502 --> 01:07:21.585
You'll see, magic happens.

01:07:25.910 --> 01:07:37.310
And since x sub
n converges to y,

01:07:37.310 --> 01:07:42.350
thus this implies that there
exists an M2 natural number

01:07:42.350 --> 01:07:47.990
such that for all n bigger
than or equal to M2--

01:07:47.990 --> 01:07:49.670
so again, this is
the part that says

01:07:49.670 --> 01:07:52.710
as long as I go far enough out
s sub n has to be close to x.

01:07:52.710 --> 01:07:54.260
Now, this is the
part that says as

01:07:54.260 --> 01:07:58.630
long as I go far enough out x
sub n has to be close to y--

01:07:58.630 --> 01:08:03.580
so that for all n bigger than
or equal to M2 x sub n minus y

01:08:03.580 --> 01:08:05.290
is less than epsilon over 2.

01:08:08.690 --> 01:08:20.319
Then since the sum M1 plus--
these are both natural numbers.

01:08:20.319 --> 01:08:28.300
This is bigger than
or equal to M1 and M2.

01:08:28.300 --> 01:08:33.640
This implies-- now, I'm going
to use these two inequalities

01:08:33.640 --> 01:08:36.550
and the triangle inequality.

01:08:36.550 --> 01:08:39.340
Then if I look at the
absolute value of x minus y,

01:08:39.340 --> 01:08:41.680
this is equal to
the absolute value

01:08:41.680 --> 01:08:46.404
of x minus x sub n
plus x sub n minus--

01:08:49.300 --> 01:08:58.420
so let me-- not x sub n, but
x sub M1 plus M2 plus x sub M1

01:08:58.420 --> 01:08:59.139
plus M2.

01:09:03.319 --> 01:09:05.060
Now, by the triangle
inequality, this

01:09:05.060 --> 01:09:15.460
is less than or equal to x
M2 plus M1 plus M2 minus y.

01:09:15.460 --> 01:09:19.189
Now, this is less
than epsilon over 2

01:09:19.189 --> 01:09:22.910
because M1 plus M2 is
bigger than or equal to M1.

01:09:26.439 --> 01:09:29.390
And for the same reason,
since plus M1 plus M2

